expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2242</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.3.3</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.3.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.3.3</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-5.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is of cohomological descent, then, for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+(S)]]></fr:tex>, the canonical map

    <fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2206</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.3.3.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.3.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.3.3.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[         \mathrm {R}\Gamma (S,K)         \to  \mathrm {R}\Gamma (S,\mathrm {R} a_*a^*K)         \simeq  \mathrm {R}\Gamma (X_\bullet ,a^*K)       \tag{5.3.3.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    is an isomorphism.
    In particular, for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> an abelian sheaf on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, we have a spectral sequence (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2"
href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2.xml"
taxon="Equation"
number="5.2.3.2" />)

    <fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2207</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.3.3.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.3.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.3.3.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \operatorname {H}^q(X_p,a_p^*F)         \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(S,F).       \tag{5.3.3.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p><fr:p>For a complex, we again have, in hypercohomology, a spectral sequence

    <fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2208</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.3.3.3</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.3.3.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.3.3.3</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^q(X_p,a_p^*K)         \Rightarrow  \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^{p+q}(S,K).       \tag{5.3.3.3}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p><fr:p>In both cases, the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[E_1^{\bullet  q}]]></fr:tex> (for fixed <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>) form a simplicial group, and
    <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[       d_1       = \sum _i (-1)^i\delta _i       \colon  E_1^{p,q}       \to  E_1^{p+1,q}.     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2243</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.3.4</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.4.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.3.4</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-5.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A continuous map <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> is of <fr:em>cohomological descent</fr:em> if the augmentation morphism of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {cosq}(X\to  S)]]></fr:tex>, namely
    <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[       \big ((X/S)^{\Delta _n}\big )_{n\geqslant 0}       \to  S,     ]]></fr:tex>
    is of cohomological descent.
    We say that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is of <fr:em>universal cohomological descent</fr:em> if, for every <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  S'\to  S]]></fr:tex>, the continuous map <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a'\colon  X\times _S S'\to  S']]></fr:tex> is of cohomological descent.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2244</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.3.5</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-5.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The fundamental results, proven in [<fr:link
type="local"
href="SD.xml"
addr="SD"
title="Techniques de descente cohomologique">SD</fr:link>], are the following.

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(I) &quot;">
        The continuous maps of universal cohomological descent form a Grothendieck topology on the category of topological spaces, which we call the <fr:em>universal cohomological descent topology</fr:em>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(II) &quot;">
        A proper (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-0.1"
href="hodge-theory-iii-0.1.xml"
number="III.0.1" />) surjective map is of universal cohomological descent.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(III) &quot;">
        A map <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> that admits sections locally on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is of universal cohomological descent.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(IV) &quot;">
        Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  X_\bullet \to  S]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-truncated augmented simplicial space (with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[-1\leqslant  k\leqslant \infty ]]></fr:tex>).
        For <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k\geqslant  n\geqslant -1]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi _n\colon \operatorname {cosq} X_\bullet \to \operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_n X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be the evident map.
        We say that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:em><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-truncated hypercover of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, for the universal cohomological descent topology</fr:em>, if the maps

        <fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2049</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.3.5.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[             (\varphi _n)_{n+1}             \colon  X_{n+1}             \to  (\operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_n X_\bullet )_{n+1}           \tag{5.3.5.1}           ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

        (for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[-1\leqslant  n\leqslant  k-1]]></fr:tex>) are of universal cohomological descent.
        If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is such a hypercover, then the simplicial space <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {cosq}(X_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> augmented over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is of cohomological descent.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(V) &quot;">
        Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> be a morphism of simplicial topological spaces augmented over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
        <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[           \begin {CD}             X_\bullet  @>a>> Y_\bullet            \\@VxVV @VVyV           \\S @= S           \end {CD}         ]]></fr:tex>
        We say that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:em>hypercover</fr:em> for the universal cohomological descent topology if the evident maps <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_n\to (\operatorname {cosq}_{n-1}^{Y_\bullet }\operatorname {sq}_{n-1}X_\bullet )_n]]></fr:tex> are of universal cohomological descent.
        If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is such a hypercover then, for every <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+(S)]]></fr:tex>,
        <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[           a^*\colon            \mathrm {R} y_*y^*K           \xrightarrow {\sim } \mathrm {R} x_*x^*K.         ]]></fr:tex>
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
