type="local"
href="SD.xml"
addr="SD"
title="Techniques de descente cohomologique">SD</fr:link>], are the following.

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(I) &quot;">
        The continuous maps of universal cohomological descent form a Grothendieck topology on the category of topological spaces, which we call the <fr:em>universal cohomological descent topology</fr:em>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(II) &quot;">
        A proper (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-0.1"
href="hodge-theory-iii-0.1.xml"
number="III.0.1" />) surjective map is of universal cohomological descent.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(III) &quot;">
        A map <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> that admits sections locally on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is of universal cohomological descent.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(IV) &quot;">
        Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  X_\bullet \to  S]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-truncated augmented simplicial space (with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[-1\leqslant  k\leqslant \infty ]]></fr:tex>).
        For <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k\geqslant  n\geqslant -1]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi _n\colon \operatorname {cosq} X_\bullet \to \operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_n X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be the evident map.
        We say that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:em><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-truncated hypercover of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, for the universal cohomological descent topology</fr:em>, if the maps

        <fr:tree
