display="block"><![CDATA[             (\varphi _n)_{n+1}             \colon  X_{n+1}             \to  (\operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_n X_\bullet )_{n+1}           \tag{5.3.5.1}           ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

        (for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[-1\leqslant  n\leqslant  k-1]]></fr:tex>) are of universal cohomological descent.
        If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is such a hypercover, then the simplicial space <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {cosq}(X_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> augmented over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is of cohomological descent.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(V) &quot;">
        Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> be a morphism of simplicial topological spaces augmented over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
        <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[           \begin {CD}             X_\bullet  @>a>> Y_\bullet            \\@VxVV @VVyV           \\S @= S           \end {CD}         ]]></fr:tex>
        We say that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:em>hypercover</fr:em> for the universal cohomological descent topology if the evident maps <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_n\to (\operatorname {cosq}_{n-1}^{Y_\bullet }\operatorname {sq}_{n-1}X_\bullet )_n]]></fr:tex> are of universal cohomological descent.
        If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is such a hypercover then, for every <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+(S)]]></fr:tex>,
        <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[           a^*\colon            \mathrm {R} y_*y^*K           \xrightarrow {\sim } \mathrm {R} x_*x^*K.         ]]></fr:tex>
      </html:li>

